'''Heptadecanoic acid''', or '''margaric acid''', is a saturated [[fatty acid]].  Its molecular formula is CH<sub>3</sub>(CH<sub>2</sub>)<sub>15</sub>COOH. It occurs as a trace component of the fat and milkfat of [[ruminant]]s,<ref>{{cite journal | journal = Nature | volume = 179 | issue = 98 | year = 1957 | doi = 10.1038/179098a0 | title = Occurrence in Butterfat of n-Heptadecanoic Acid (Margaric Acid) | author =R. P. Hansen, F. B. Shorland and N. June Cooke | pages = 98| bibcode = 1957Natur.179...98H }}</ref> but it does not occur in any natural animal or vegetable fat at high concentrations.<ref name="lexicon">{{cite journal |year=2001 |title=Lexicon of lipid nutrition (IUPAC Technical Report) |journal=Pure and Applied Chemistry |volume=73 |issue=4 |pages=685–744 |url=http://iupac.org/publications/pac/73/4/0685/ |doi=10.1351/pac200173040685 |last1=Beare-Rogers |first1=J. |last2=Dieffenbacher |first2=A. |last3=Holm |first3=J.V. }}</ref>  For example, it only comprises 2.2% of the fats from the fruit of the [[durian]] species ''[[Durio graveolens]]''.<ref name="Nasaruddin">{{cite journal|last1=Nasaruddin|first1=Mohd hanif|last2=Noor|first2=Noor Qhairul Izzreen Mohd|last3=Mamat|first3=Hasmadi|title=Komposisi Proksimat dan Komponen Asid Lemak Durian Kuning (Durio graveolens) Sabah|journal=Sains Malaysiana|date=2013|volume=42|issue=9|pages=1283–1288|url=http://www.ukm.my/jsm/pdf_files/SM-PDF-42-9-2013/11%20Mohd%20Hanif.pdf|accessdate=28 November 2017|trans-title=Proximate and Fatty Acid Composition of Sabah Yellow Durian (Durio graveolens)|language=Malay|format=PDF|issn=0126-6039|oclc=857479186}}</ref> However, in the 19th and early 20th centuries, there were numerous reports of the acid being found in natural fats in significant amounts. Most likely, these were cases of misidentifying a [[eutectic mixture]] of palmitic and stearic acids.<ref>[https://books.google.co.il/books?id=vW0IAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA116 Чёт или нечет? Занимательные очерки по химии], pages 116-120</ref> Salts and [[ester]]s of heptadecanoic acid are called '''heptadecanoates'''.

