[[File:Netroots Nation 2008 (2677975512).jpg|thumb|right|Man holding a sign promoting the campaign outside of the venue for [[Netroots Nation]] 2008]] '''Project Hot Seat''' is a campaign started by [[Greenpeace]]. Its goal is to apply intense pressure on members of The [[United States Congress]] in order to implement policies that will curb and cut U.S. greenhouse gas emissions, and what [[Phil Radford]], [[Greenpeace]] Executive Director said was the "kind of organizing that is going to be key to making the environmental movement into a viable political force in Congress and around the country.".<ref name="[[Grist.org]]">{{cite web |publisher=[[Grist.org]] |url= http://grist.org/article/2009-04-14-greenpeaces-new-leader-talks/ |title= Greenpeace’s new leader talks up need for a green grassroots | author=Kate Sheppard| date=2009-04-15}}</ref>
==Purpose==
Some of Project Hot Seats aims include reaching a national cap and trade system that makes real reductions within a decade, a national renewable energy standard of at least 20% by 2020, and an increase in average fuel economy to 40 mpg.<ref>[http://members.greenpeace.org/hotseat/National/default/about_us/ Greenpeace: Greenpeace - Project Hotseat<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305160115/http://members.greenpeace.org/hotseat/National/default/about_us/ |date=2008-03-05 }}</ref> Project members work to raise awareness of [[global warming]] by organizing events such as The International Day of Action. This was a project in which volunteers throughout the world held rallies and outreach events to raise concern for global warming. The most recent was held on December 8, 2007. Some of the events included 25 people taking a polar bear swim in Puget Sound.<ref>[http://gallery.globalclimatecampaign.org/node/2767 Greenpeace banner in the water | Global Climate Campaign Gallery<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720153701/http://gallery.globalclimatecampaign.org/node/2767 |date=2008-07-20 }}</ref> The project also engages in human art to get its message across. Over 300 participants in Florida sat on a beach in the shape of the state of Florida with the southern tip dipping into the ocean. Below the state they used their bodies to spell out the words "Save our State".<ref>[http://racanna.com/Greenpeace-protest.html Greenpeace protest aims to fire up Congress over global warming - A GREENPEACE CAMPAIGN ON GLOBAL WARMING TARGETS THE SHAW-KLEIN RACE<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
